23:30.000 --> 23:40.000
Yeah. Just to put a little bit of pressure on what you were saying first. I mean, because there's a version I think where the embrace of impermanence,

23:40.000 --> 23:49.000
the supposed embrace of impermanence is actually a very established way of trying to gain eternity in the sense of like becoming

23:49.000 --> 23:56.000
immune or invulnerable to the experience of loss, starting to say like, so a lot of these strategies, we have them in Western stoicism for example,

23:56.000 --> 24:03.000
where like the reason you're told that it would be wise to stop being future-oriented is because when you're future-oriented,

24:03.000 --> 24:11.000
you're giving hostages to the future to something that's unpredictable, and you're attached to something that can be taken away from you.

24:11.000 --> 24:22.000
