30:35.000 --> 30:42.000
but again, I think once one distinguishes between aspirations to live on with specializations to eternity,

30:42.000 --> 30:47.000
I think some of the discontinuities that you outline are less forceful.

30:47.000 --> 30:56.000
So as distinct from, say, Christian aspiration to eternity, the ambition for the artwork to live on,

30:56.000 --> 31:00.000
you know, I mean, if you think about the poetic expressions of this in Shakespeare, or Keats, et cetera,

31:00.000 --> 31:06.000
there's an intense awareness, both of the possibility to live on, say, through the breadth of the speaker

31:06.000 --> 31:11.000
who will reanimate the poem, but there's also an intense sense of like, this is not a given,

31:11.000 --> 31:19.000
it can just be left to die, not reanimated by the reader, and even if it is reanimated, that's not about eternity.

31:19.000 --> 31:25.000
