31:25.000 --> 31:31.000
What we call poetic immortality, I think, is actually an investment in a certain form of living on,

31:31.000 --> 31:37.000
and I think we can, and which is, you know, another version of that is what you yourself recognize as relevant in contemporary world,

31:37.000 --> 31:40.000
that I want to live for another week or another two weeks.

31:40.000 --> 31:48.000
So that dimension of our aspiration to live on, I think we can recognize across the ages much more,

31:48.000 --> 31:53.000
and I think that maybe we can have it more explicit now because we don't have to be the same extent

31:53.000 --> 32:02.000
of investment in an opposing concept of eternity, but I do think that, I mean, I'm someone who works professional literature,

32:02.000 --> 32:12.000
and I, as you do too, and I certainly don't feel alienated from the pathos of key, so Shakespeare, in their investment in poetry's capacity to live on.

32:12.000 --> 32:17.000
I just don't think that has anything to do with a commitment to eternity or a norm, in very many ways,

32:17.000 --> 32:24.000
a materialist conception because it depends on the material of the poems, surviving, reanimated, etc.

32:24.000 --> 32:33.000
Yeah, well, maybe it's because in the classical or Christian world you had a confidence in the perpetuity of human civilization.

32:33.000 --> 32:38.000
