01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:07.000
It was a big difference in regret and fear.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:16.000
I don't think it's not regret because it's not past-oriented. It's the prospect of a future in which you will not be.

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:20.000
And so, I think regret is past-oriented and fear is future-oriented.

01:25:20.000 --> 01:25:23.000
So I think that's adequately called a fear.

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:31.000
That I apprehend the possibility of my not being, and precisely because I have an investment in continuing to be,

01:25:31.000 --> 01:25:33.000
that scares me.

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:38.000
And it doesn't seem like that's a category mistake or irrational.

01:25:38.000 --> 01:25:42.000
I think there's a very coherent logic to that.

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:49.000
It seems to me that it's like what Rob said, that a lot of the fears are based on experiences from childhood that we've already had,

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:53.000
and that we reorganize them around dying.

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:57.000
And so we're afraid that we're going into the dark alone, or we're afraid we're going to fall forever,

01:25:57.000 --> 01:26:05.000
or that some things going to be destroyed, that we've already had those deep fears, and they become reorganized in dying.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:07.000
Even if you're religious, you have those fears?

01:26:07.000 --> 01:26:08.000
Oh, yeah.

01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:09.000
Yeah.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:11.000
Because you don't believe your religion.

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:15.000
Well, dying is a physical, a very physical activity.

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:20.000
