01:28:26.000 --> 01:28:33.000
and what you said was very evocative, is the fact that what makes it both

01:28:33.000 --> 01:28:41.000
difficult but also meaningful to be alive is that you have both permanence and impermanence.

01:28:41.000 --> 01:28:48.000
If you only had absolute impermanence, there wouldn't be any problem because you wouldn't experience the loss of anything.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:28:51.000
Everything would immediately disappear.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:58.000
And if you had absolute permanence, likewise, nothing would be an issue because everything would just be what it is.

01:28:58.000 --> 01:29:05.000
So the key to thinking about mortality in the general sense, I think, is to think about the co-impicational permanence in permanence.

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:08.000
That like, things last while also disappearing.

01:29:08.000 --> 01:29:11.000
Things last while also being possible to cease to be.

01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:17.000
And that's where both the passion and the agony of being alive arises from that intersection of permanence and impermanence.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:23.000
And I mean, I'm sure as a surgeon you've had particularly vivid experiences of this, but I think that that is the structure.

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:28.000
And that's also why attempts to escape mortality can either be done like,

01:29:28.000 --> 01:29:31.000
oh, that's just an absolute impermanence. Everything disappears and I don't care.

01:29:31.000 --> 01:29:32.000
That's fine.

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:34.000
Then of course, nothing hurts me.

01:29:34.000 --> 01:29:38.000
Or I imagine that there's something absolutely permanent that I don't have to worry about.

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:43.000
But I think both of those paths are flights from what we are and how things matter to us.

01:29:43.000 --> 01:29:47.000
And we should not indulge those flights.

